1
00:00:01,160 --> 00:00:03,958
- That's not the Girl Scout salute.
- Oh.

2
00:00:04,040 --> 00:00:06,349
- Wrong hand, Peterson.
- Oh, well, okay.

3
00:00:06,440 --> 00:00:09,193
So I was never a Girl Scout,
but I'm telling you the truth, Brackett.

4
00:00:13,600 --> 00:00:14,715
I swear.

5
00:00:14,800 --> 00:00:17,519
Okay, so tell me.
What's LDF?

6
00:00:17,600 --> 00:00:21,878
"LDF is a genetically engineered hormone
for dairy cows. It could be the fir..."

7
00:00:21,960 --> 00:00:25,157
Somebody's trying to kill us
over a cow hormone?

8
00:00:25,240 --> 00:00:27,959
"Could be the first commercial success
of genetic engineering...

9
00:00:28,040 --> 00:00:30,349
that directly affects food
for humans."

10
00:00:30,440 --> 00:00:35,195
"Milk Hormone Stirs Fear."
Okay, now we're talkin'.

11
00:00:35,280 --> 00:00:38,989
"LDF milk tests will be reviewed
by State's Agricultural
Committee Chairwoman...

12
00:00:39,080 --> 00:00:41,435
Gayle Robbins."
Bingo!

13
00:00:41,520 --> 00:00:43,317
- You wanna know about LDF?
- Yeah.

14
00:00:43,400 --> 00:00:44,799
You've come to
the right place.

15
00:00:44,880 --> 00:00:46,791
- In English, Sam, please.
- Okay, here's the deal.

16
00:00:46,880 --> 00:00:49,997
Normally it takes a calf two years to
mature into a milk-producing cow, right?

17
00:00:50,080 --> 00:00:53,231
So, Chess figured, why wait
that long taking care of a calf?
It's not making you any money.

18
00:00:53,320 --> 00:00:56,915
So they invent this hormone LDF. They
shoot that stuff into a newborn calf.

19
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:00,675
Nine months later, you got
yourself a full-grown,
milk-producing, moneymaking...

20
00:01:00,760 --> 00:01:03,797
- Franken-cow.
- That's exactly what I thought at first.

21
00:01:03,880 --> 00:01:06,348
But then from what we hear the cows
are healthy, and the tests show...

22
00:01:06,440 --> 00:01:08,431
I hates these tours!

23
00:01:08,520 --> 00:01:11,159
And the tests show that the milk's,
uh, pure. So, there you go.

24
00:01:11,240 --> 00:01:13,708
Say, what kind of profits can
Chess make on a thing like this?

25
00:01:13,800 --> 00:01:17,076
Thing?
This thing, my boy, could revolutionize
the entire worldwide dairy industry.

26
00:01:17,160 --> 00:01:19,799
Potentially the biggest moneymaker
that a chemical company has seen...

27
00:01:19,880 --> 00:01:21,757
- since NutraSweet.
- Yeah?

28
00:01:21,840 --> 00:01:23,796
- Yeah.
- So, how much can they make?

29
00:01:23,880 --> 00:01:26,440
Oh, somewhere in the neighbourhood
of a billion dollars a year.

30
00:01:26,520 --> 00:01:30,399
- Oh, nice neighbourhood.
- Yeah. I wouldn't mind
living there myself.

31
00:01:30,480 --> 00:01:32,391
Oh, hi.
You got out early.

32
00:01:32,480 --> 00:01:36,519
One of the advantages
of being chairperson.
You get to adjourn the meetings.

33
00:01:36,600 --> 00:01:38,636
- How'd that school board thing work out?
- Oh, nothing to worry about.

34
00:01:38,720 --> 00:01:41,473
- Uh, these are friends
of mine from Chicago.
- Oh, hi. Gayle Robbins.

35
00:01:41,560 --> 00:01:42,959
- Peter Brackett from the <i>Chronicle.</i>
- Yes.

36
00:01:43,040 --> 00:01:44,109
- And this is Sabrina, uh...
- Peterson.

37
00:01:44,200 --> 00:01:46,156
Of the <i>Globe.</i>
Sorry.

38
00:01:46,240 --> 00:01:48,708
Yes. It's nice to meet you.
Sam, are we having a press conference?

39
00:01:48,800 --> 00:01:50,950
No, no, no. They're just doing
some research on LDF, that's all.

40
00:01:51,040 --> 00:01:52,632
- Really?
- Yep.
- What do you think?

41
00:01:52,720 --> 00:01:54,631
We were just gonna ask you
that same question,
being the head of the committee.

42
00:01:54,720 --> 00:01:56,915
Uh, it really doesn't behove
the Senator to render an opinion
on that matter...

43
00:01:57,000 --> 00:01:59,230
- Sam!
- All right, go ahead and render.

44
00:01:59,320 --> 00:02:02,437
Give me a buzz after the FD A completes
its review. We'll talk then.

45
00:02:02,520 --> 00:02:04,795
- Ready, Senator?
- Sam.

46
00:02:04,880 --> 00:02:07,394
I know, Pete. You got like a thousand
questions, right? Okay, okay.

47
00:02:07,480 --> 00:02:12,349
Look, I got a, an hour here.
Okay? What do you say I take
both of you to dinner, huh?

48
00:02:12,440 --> 00:02:14,271
On the house?

49
00:02:16,280 --> 00:02:18,589
Two New Yorks, rare.

50
00:02:18,680 --> 00:02:22,434
And one steamed vegetable plate,
no salt, no oil, no butter.

51
00:02:22,520 --> 00:02:24,431
Thank you.

52
00:02:24,520 --> 00:02:27,478
So, you started to say that during
Vietnam, Chess manufactured...

53
00:02:27,560 --> 00:02:31,314
Oh, you know, just things like
napalm, Agent Orange, you know?

54
00:02:31,400 --> 00:02:32,799
All that wonderful stuff.

55
00:02:32,880 --> 00:02:35,155
And then the war ended and
their profits really dried up.

56
00:02:35,240 --> 00:02:37,879
For a while, it looked like the
company was on its last legs.

57
00:02:37,960 --> 00:02:40,076
And then, along comes
the genetic revolution.

58
00:02:40,160 --> 00:02:43,675
And boy,
things really heated up for them.
LDF could put them right back on top.

59
00:02:43,760 --> 00:02:46,194
- What's the Chess family like?
- Oh, boy.

60
00:02:46,280 --> 00:02:50,353
Well, the old man's
a real zealot, you know?
He's kinda like a Ross Perot wannabe.

61
00:02:50,440 --> 00:02:53,079
His kid, Willy, kind of runs things now.
I don't know too much about him.

62
00:02:53,160 --> 00:02:55,230
I think he went to Yale,
and then straight to work for Daddy.

63
00:02:55,320 --> 00:02:58,153
- Did you know him at Yale?
- Uh-uh, uh-uh.

64
00:02:58,240 --> 00:03:00,595
No, I think he's younger than me. How
did you remember that I went to Yale?

65
00:03:00,680 --> 00:03:04,116
That is incredible.
You've got such an amazing memory.
I can't remember my own name.

66
00:03:04,200 --> 00:03:08,273
It's possible that I met him
at school, but I doubt it.
I don't even think he graduated.

67
00:03:08,360 --> 00:03:11,352
What year would he have been
if he had graduated?

68
00:03:11,440 --> 00:03:13,476
I don't know.
Let me think. Uh...

69
00:03:13,560 --> 00:03:16,950
- What year did you graduate?
- Me? '73. No, '74.

70
00:03:17,040 --> 00:03:19,349
So that would make him class of
'76, '77, something like that.

71
00:03:19,440 --> 00:03:21,795
You know, Gayle's met him a few times.
He's supposed to be a nice guy.

72
00:03:21,880 --> 00:03:25,714
Not exactly a rocket scientist,
but he...

73
00:03:25,800 --> 00:03:29,873
What's going on here exactly, guys?
I mean, why are you
so interested in LDF, huh?

74
00:03:29,960 --> 00:03:34,033
Oh, Peterson here is
a big milk drinker. That's all.

75
00:03:34,120 --> 00:03:35,951
Oh, well, it d...
It does a body good.

76
00:03:37,320 --> 00:03:40,198
Sorry. C'mon, you're not
gonna tell me?

77
00:03:40,280 --> 00:03:43,158
It's gotta be somethin' big if
both the <i>Globe</i> and the <i>Chronicle</i>
are in bed together on it.

78
00:03:46,480 --> 00:03:48,789
I wouldn't say we're exactly
in bed together.

79
00:03:50,760 --> 00:03:53,718
Cheque, please.

80
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:03,949
Oh. Okay, now.
In case you have any more questions...

81
00:04:04,040 --> 00:04:07,350
or if you finally decide
to tell me what you've
actually got up your sleeve...

82
00:04:07,440 --> 00:04:09,351
- here's my card, Pete.
It's got my direct dial on it.
- Oh, thanks, Sam.

83
00:04:09,440 --> 00:04:10,589
- Where are you parked?
- In the lot over there.

84
00:04:10,680 --> 00:04:13,069
Oh, perfect.
We're gonna pass by...

85
00:04:13,160 --> 00:04:16,914
- the best frozen yogurt joint
in the entire state.
- Yeah?

86
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:18,991
It's on Peterson.

87
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:23,319
- Look out!
- Sam!

88
00:04:23,400 --> 00:04:25,960
Move!

89
00:04:29,600 --> 00:04:31,477
Sam, are you okay?

90
00:04:31,560 --> 00:04:34,791
What the hell
was that all about?

91
00:04:38,760 --> 00:04:40,591
Medwick, it's me.
Just checking in.

92
00:04:40,680 --> 00:04:42,671
Listen, I've put together a
"just the facts, ma'am" kind of thing...

93
00:04:42,760 --> 00:04:44,079
and wanted to
run it by you, okay?

94
00:04:44,160 --> 00:04:46,230
<i>- They know you're there?</i>
- Uh, no.

95
00:04:46,320 --> 00:04:48,117
- I guess so far
they don't know we're here.
<i>- You're lucky.</i>

96
00:04:48,200 --> 00:04:51,158
Yeah, real lucky.
So, here's what we know:

97
00:04:51,240 --> 00:04:53,356
Beekman was the head researcher
on LDF.

98
00:04:53,440 --> 00:04:55,908
He retires mysteriously,
then dies a week later.

99
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:59,959
His son boards a train with something
in his briefcase that his dad sent him.

100
00:05:00,040 --> 00:05:04,431
The train crashes, the son dies,
and the briefcase is stolen.

101
00:05:04,520 --> 00:05:07,956
The kid who stole it is murdered,
but before he dies he writes
the initials "LD" on his palm.

102
00:05:08,040 --> 00:05:11,316
LD means LDF, and LDF means
a billion dollars a year.

103
00:05:11,400 --> 00:05:14,597
So you tell me.
All this adds up to...

104
00:05:14,680 --> 00:05:17,558
Good morning, everyone,
and welcome to Chess Chemical.

105
00:05:17,640 --> 00:05:21,758
Our first stop on today's tour
will be the Chess Family
Science Discovery Centre.

106
00:05:21,840 --> 00:05:25,469
Now, as we walk in pairs
down the Biology of Tomorrow corridor...

107
00:05:25,560 --> 00:05:29,951
I'd like to point out some of the
everyday products created here at Chess.

108
00:05:30,040 --> 00:05:32,952
For example, the cold medicine
that I forgot to take this morning...

109
00:05:33,040 --> 00:05:36,157
as well as the disposable diapers
I used for my little one last night.

110
00:05:36,240 --> 00:05:37,878
Now, as we continue on...

111
00:05:37,960 --> 00:05:42,078
Extension 307 is a 72-year-old
cafeteria worker named Sadie.

112
00:05:42,160 --> 00:05:43,991
Hair net,
orthopaedic shoes.

113
00:05:44,080 --> 00:05:45,638
Are you sure?
Maybe it was 3-0-something else.

114
00:05:45,720 --> 00:05:48,917
No, no, no. I'm positive.
Here, look.

115
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:53,232
Well, do you wanna get out of here,
or take a stroll down
the Biology of Tomorrow corridor?

116
00:05:53,320 --> 00:05:56,869
Rule number one of
investigative reporting, Peterson,
is find out what you're up against.

117
00:05:56,960 --> 00:06:01,556
- Let's stroll.
- What's rule number two?

118
00:06:01,640 --> 00:06:06,270
Stay clear of all surveillance cameras
when visiting the lair of the enemy.

119
00:06:06,920 --> 00:06:09,354
Thanks.

120
00:06:11,640 --> 00:06:14,359
- Thank you.
- No problem.

121
00:06:14,440 --> 00:06:17,716
- Wilson Chess.
- Sabrina Peterson.

122
00:06:17,800 --> 00:06:22,032
- And Mr Peterson?
- Actually, the name's Brackett.

123
00:06:22,120 --> 00:06:24,588
Peter Brackett,
the writer.

124
00:06:24,680 --> 00:06:28,593
Of course. Well, what brings you
to this neck of the woods?

125
00:06:28,680 --> 00:06:30,989
I'm doin' a little research
on a new novel, Wilson.

126
00:06:31,080 --> 00:06:32,911
You're kidding?
What, here at Chess?

127
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:36,231
- Mm-hmm.
- What's the new one about?

128
00:06:36,320 --> 00:06:39,676
It's a murder mystery set against
the backdrop of a chemical company.

129
00:06:39,760 --> 00:06:44,550
Sounds intriguing, but I'm always
a sucker for a good murder yarn.

130
00:06:44,640 --> 00:06:50,033
- Aren't you, Miss Peterson?
- As long as the bad guy gets
it in the end, I'm happy.

131
00:06:50,120 --> 00:06:55,638
W-Well, have fun.
And don't forget to change
the names to protect the innocent.

132
00:06:55,720 --> 00:06:58,280
So much for rule number three:
Avoid insulting...

133
00:06:58,360 --> 00:07:00,316
the men who may be trying
to kill you.

134
00:07:00,400 --> 00:07:02,675
- Oh, uh, I was just looking for
you, sir. Here, look at this.
- Hello.

135
00:07:02,760 --> 00:07:04,432
- It's fine.
- You look very nice today.
- Thank you.

136
00:07:04,520 --> 00:07:07,080
- Check this one out.
- We missed you for lunch. It was...

137
00:07:07,160 --> 00:07:09,116
...right through to
the research farm behind me...

138
00:07:09,200 --> 00:07:12,272
where scientists are fine-tuning
Mother Nature with such innovative...

139
00:07:12,360 --> 00:07:16,797
products for the future as the
Livestock Development Factor, LDF.

140
00:07:16,880 --> 00:07:18,757
Now, if you'll come with me,
I'd like to show you a film...

141
00:07:18,840 --> 00:07:21,752
that highlights some of the exciting
things we're doing here at Chess.

142
00:07:21,840 --> 00:07:24,513
Don't worry, parents.
It's G-rated.

143
00:07:24,600 --> 00:07:26,750
- Hey, where'd you guys go on your break?
- We looked for you.

144
00:07:26,840 --> 00:07:28,796
- We did.
- Oh, I had to go to the lab.

145
00:07:28,880 --> 00:07:32,759
Rule number four: Get close to someone
who's close to the enemy.

146
00:07:32,840 --> 00:07:35,149
How am I supposed
to calm down?

147
00:07:35,240 --> 00:07:37,231
You promised me this was going
to be taken care of...

148
00:07:37,320 --> 00:07:40,073
and now they are here
in my building.

149
00:07:43,240 --> 00:07:46,277
Ernesto, I can't
handle this any more.

150
00:07:46,360 --> 00:07:49,397
Just make it happen.

151
00:07:49,480 --> 00:07:51,869
- You want us to pick you up
at Ruby's tonight?
- Oh, I'll meet you there.

152
00:07:51,960 --> 00:07:55,316
It's better if we take our own cars,
in case one of us gets lucky.

153
00:07:55,400 --> 00:07:58,198
You mean, in case
there's a miracle, right?

154
00:07:58,280 --> 00:07:59,952
You never know.

155
00:08:46,960 --> 00:08:49,872
Well, what do you know?
Huh.

156
00:09:40,040 --> 00:09:42,952
Evans, this is great. This is good.
You got any leads on 'im?

157
00:09:43,040 --> 00:09:44,871
<i>- Pete, I'm looking for</i>
<i>some more information on...</i>
- Come in.

158
00:09:44,960 --> 00:09:49,078
<i>- Hello? Mr Brackett?</i>
- Hi.

159
00:09:49,160 --> 00:09:50,832
<i>Mr Brackett, we haven't come up</i>
<i>with anything yet, but when we do...</i>

160
00:09:50,920 --> 00:09:54,310
Yeah, okay. Well, stay on it
and I'll check with you later.

161
00:09:54,400 --> 00:09:55,799
Yeah.

162
00:09:55,880 --> 00:09:57,757
Interesting news.

163
00:09:57,840 --> 00:09:59,956
It seems Willy Chess
did go to Yale.

164
00:10:00,040 --> 00:10:02,873
- Who's Ernesto Vargas?
- Well, that's the interesting news.

165
00:10:02,960 --> 00:10:06,236
The reason Sam was confused about
whether or not Chess graduated...

166
00:10:06,320 --> 00:10:08,470
- is because he was expelled.
- For?

167
00:10:08,560 --> 00:10:09,879
Burning down
the English Department.

168
00:10:09,960 --> 00:10:12,030
Somethin' about a problem
with one of his professors.

169
00:10:12,120 --> 00:10:15,908
Young Willy and his cohort,
this South American kid Vargas...

170
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:20,630
they decided to torch the place
for revenge, and they were
caught and properly booted out.

171
00:10:20,720 --> 00:10:22,995
A fire back then,
a fire at Beekman's.

172
00:10:23,080 --> 00:10:26,117
A South American friend,
a South American assassin.

173
00:10:26,200 --> 00:10:28,668
- Where's Vargas now?
- Evans can't seem to get a line on him.

174
00:10:28,760 --> 00:10:32,116
- Maybe Sam could help.
- Yeah. Good idea.

175
00:10:32,200 --> 00:10:34,031
Good idea.

176
00:10:37,800 --> 00:10:39,870
You don't know
what I did with his, uh...

177
00:10:44,320 --> 00:10:46,197
Thank you.

178
00:10:49,360 --> 00:10:53,273
By the way, I dressed like this
because I figured this is the way...

179
00:10:53,360 --> 00:10:55,430
you're supposed to dress
at these pickup places...

180
00:10:55,520 --> 00:10:58,398
and I didn't want
to stand out or anything.

181
00:10:58,480 --> 00:11:01,916
Yeah. No chance of anyone
noticing you, Peterson.

182
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:04,116
- That's good thinking.
<i>- Sam Smotherman's office.</i>

183
00:11:04,200 --> 00:11:05,713
- Hi. Is he in?
<i>- Who's calling, please?</i>

184
00:11:05,800 --> 00:11:07,631
- Peter Brackett.
<i>- Just a minute.</i>

185
00:11:07,720 --> 00:11:11,156
By the way, Peterson, that reminds me.
We never did finish
that other discussion.

186
00:11:11,240 --> 00:11:12,719
- What other discussion?
<i>- Pete, hello.</i>

187
00:11:12,800 --> 00:11:14,552
Sam, how ya doin'?

188
00:11:14,640 --> 00:11:16,596
Well, I'm all right,
believe it or not.

189
00:11:16,680 --> 00:11:19,672
Well, I knew you'd recover. Listen,
can you check on an old Yalie for me?

190
00:11:19,760 --> 00:11:21,876
A name came up. We can't seem
to get a lead on the guy.

191
00:11:21,960 --> 00:11:23,632
I'm sorry. Just one second.
Sure. Who is he?

192
00:11:23,720 --> 00:11:25,870
<i>Well, he was at Yale</i>
<i>the same time as Willy Chess.</i>

193
00:11:25,960 --> 00:11:29,077
- His name is, uh, Ernesto Vargas.
- Bargas?

194
00:11:29,160 --> 00:11:31,355
<i>No, no, no.</i>
<i>Vargas with a "V" like Victor.</i>

195
00:11:31,440 --> 00:11:34,352
Oh, Vargas. That doesn't sound familiar,
but I'll check him out.

196
00:11:34,440 --> 00:11:37,113
All right.
Well, look, I'm gonna be in and out,
so if you come up with anything...

197
00:11:37,200 --> 00:11:40,431
<i>like where he is or how we can reach</i>
<i>him, call my office, ask for Evans.</i>

198
00:11:40,520 --> 00:11:42,511
Yeah, I'll make a deal with you,
though. I find this Vargas guy...

199
00:11:42,600 --> 00:11:44,875
then you're gonna clue me in
on what you're workin' on?

200
00:11:44,960 --> 00:11:47,633
If he finds Vargas, will we clue
him in on what we're working on?

201
00:11:47,720 --> 00:11:49,119
No.

202
00:11:50,800 --> 00:11:54,031
You got it, buddy! Thanks a lot.
I'll see ya later.

203
00:11:56,120 --> 00:11:59,476
Rule number five, Peterson:
Always humour those who can help you.

204
00:11:59,560 --> 00:12:02,199
Now, what other conversation
did you want to finish?

205
00:12:02,280 --> 00:12:04,748
Oh, the one about me
wanting to get you in the sack.

206
00:12:04,840 --> 00:12:07,195
Oh, that. Well, forget it.
I didn't really think...

207
00:12:07,280 --> 00:12:10,033
No, no, no, Peterson.
This is important.

208
00:12:10,120 --> 00:12:14,511
I want you to know that I see you
strictly as a fellow newspaperman.

209
00:12:14,600 --> 00:12:16,272
I mean that sincerely.

210
00:12:16,360 --> 00:12:20,273
I see you as nothing else,
and I never will.

211
00:12:20,360 --> 00:12:22,555
You have my word on it.

212
00:12:22,640 --> 00:12:24,835
- I do?
