439
00:27:49,160 --> 00:27:51,515
Congratulations.
Right this way.

440
00:27:51,600 --> 00:27:53,909
- You kids next?
- Us?

441
00:27:54,000 --> 00:27:58,198
- Yes! Yes! Yes, we are. We're next.
- Isn't this rather sudden?

442
00:27:58,280 --> 00:27:59,952
Come, come, come.
Don't be shy.

443
00:28:00,040 --> 00:28:02,679
My name is Ray. I'll be conducting
the service this evening.

444
00:28:02,760 --> 00:28:04,637
Please take a position
in front of the podium...

445
00:28:04,720 --> 00:28:08,599
and I'll acquaint you with the
<i>accoutrement</i> we have at our disposal.

446
00:28:08,680 --> 00:28:11,638
We have flowers,
fresh or silk.

447
00:28:11,720 --> 00:28:16,794
We have rings, veil, tux,
yarmulke, if you so desire.

448
00:28:16,880 --> 00:28:19,713
- Music, prerecorded or live...
- We'll take the works.

449
00:28:19,800 --> 00:28:22,439
Yes. The works, Sandra.

450
00:28:22,520 --> 00:28:27,196
Spare no expense on such
a marvellous and holy occasion.

451
00:28:27,280 --> 00:28:30,397
That's a 42,
and it looks like a winner.

452
00:28:30,480 --> 00:28:33,756
Please place this
on the apex of the skull.

453
00:28:33,840 --> 00:28:35,910
Very good.
Would you folks prefer the...

454
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:38,560
long or the abridged service
this evening?

455
00:28:38,640 --> 00:28:40,835
Uh, just do us a favour.
Just go through the motions. Uh...

456
00:28:40,920 --> 00:28:43,036
- Just start.
- Just start? Why don't we just start?

457
00:28:43,120 --> 00:28:45,918
Sandra, if you will.
I'll need your names.

458
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:47,672
- Peterson.
- Brackett.

459
00:28:47,760 --> 00:28:52,436
Peterson, you and Brackett
have decided to unite your love.

460
00:28:52,520 --> 00:28:57,036
May you cherish
this sacred moment...

461
00:28:58,960 --> 00:29:00,552
forever.
Rings.

462
00:29:01,480 --> 00:29:03,869
As I ask Brackett...

463
00:29:03,960 --> 00:29:06,793
do you take Peterson
to be your wedded wife...

464
00:29:06,880 --> 00:29:09,440
promising to cherish
and protect her...

465
00:29:09,520 --> 00:29:11,988
be it in good fortune
and adversity?

466
00:29:12,080 --> 00:29:13,672
- Is he here?
- Yes!

467
00:29:13,760 --> 00:29:17,594
Yes? And do you take Brackett
to be your wedded husband...

468
00:29:17,680 --> 00:29:20,433
promising to cherish
and protect him...

469
00:29:20,520 --> 00:29:23,034
be it in good fortune
and adversity?

470
00:29:23,120 --> 00:29:25,350
- If he comes any closer,
we're out the rear exit.
- Okay.

471
00:29:25,440 --> 00:29:28,716
Okay. And so,
by the powers vested in me...

472
00:29:28,800 --> 00:29:30,995
by the great state
of Nevada...

473
00:29:31,080 --> 00:29:33,799
I pronounce you
husband and wife.

474
00:29:35,240 --> 00:29:36,798
<i>Mazel tov.</i>

475
00:29:47,280 --> 00:29:49,475
I'm coming up empty
on this guy Vargas.

476
00:29:49,560 --> 00:29:51,676
And your friend Sam
called twice.

477
00:29:51,760 --> 00:29:54,399
He said that he can't find
anybody who knew him at Yale.

478
00:29:54,480 --> 00:29:58,268
<i>Oh, how's Peterson?</i>
<i>Is she still driving you crazy?</i>

479
00:30:00,120 --> 00:30:04,238
More than you can imagine.
I'll talk to you tomorrow.

480
00:30:04,320 --> 00:30:06,629
- Anything?
- Not yet.

481
00:30:08,720 --> 00:30:11,280
- You hungry?
- Yeah, a little.

482
00:30:14,720 --> 00:30:16,438
Thanks.

483
00:30:18,080 --> 00:30:20,469
To the bravest girl
I ever met.

484
00:30:20,560 --> 00:30:22,790
Why? Because I've managed
to stay alive?

485
00:30:22,880 --> 00:30:25,758
Oh, no, no!
Because you married me.

486
00:30:35,880 --> 00:30:39,793
Am I really looking
at a heart-shaped turkey burger?

487
00:30:41,920 --> 00:30:45,629
You know, if anyone told me two weeks
ago I'd be married to Peter Brackett...

488
00:30:45,720 --> 00:30:47,836
Oh, no, no, no, no. Don't worry.
I already checked.

489
00:30:47,920 --> 00:30:50,593
We can have it annulled
in the morning.

490
00:30:50,680 --> 00:30:54,070
Oh, you did?
Good.

491
00:30:54,160 --> 00:30:58,312
Well, a 12-hour marriage.
Even shorter than my first one.

492
00:30:59,600 --> 00:31:01,238
Peterson,
you were married before?

493
00:31:01,320 --> 00:31:03,515
You find that so hard
to imagine?

494
00:31:03,600 --> 00:31:08,355
No, no. I'm just sort of particular
about who my wives have been married to.

495
00:31:08,440 --> 00:31:11,716
- Who was he?
- Name's O'Connor.

496
00:31:11,800 --> 00:31:15,315
Of Peterson, Peterson
and O'Connor.

497
00:31:15,400 --> 00:31:18,312
He's extremely close
with my parents.

498
00:31:18,400 --> 00:31:22,109
- Well, you've been married
before, right?
- I tried it briefly.

499
00:31:22,200 --> 00:31:25,351
- Didn't like it?
- No, actually it was my wife
who had the complaint.

500
00:31:25,440 --> 00:31:29,115
She said I was never home. She said
I loved newspapering more than her...

501
00:31:29,200 --> 00:31:32,875
She said she'd never mean as much to you
as the story you were working on.

502
00:31:32,960 --> 00:31:35,713
- She said she was jealous of the boys...
- In the city room.

503
00:31:35,800 --> 00:31:39,031
- Yeah!
- Funny.
- Yeah.

504
00:31:39,120 --> 00:31:42,510
She's now married to a brilliant CPA
with an amazing sweater collection.

505
00:31:42,600 --> 00:31:45,353
- Bet he's home every night.
- Like clockwork.

506
00:31:45,440 --> 00:31:47,715
- That's what they like.
- Regularity.

507
00:31:47,800 --> 00:31:50,394
Yeah.

508
00:31:56,000 --> 00:31:58,434
You know, Brackett...

509
00:31:58,520 --> 00:32:02,274
some guys...

510
00:32:02,360 --> 00:32:06,273
might try to take advantage of
a situation like this, but not you.

511
00:32:06,360 --> 00:32:08,316
No, no.

512
00:32:08,400 --> 00:32:11,676
I know this is
the one area...

513
00:32:11,760 --> 00:32:14,558
- where I can completely trust you.
- Mm-hmm.

514
00:32:17,000 --> 00:32:18,797
So, which side of the heart
do you want?

515
00:32:18,880 --> 00:32:21,838
- We're sleeping in shifts. Remember?
- Yeah, right. I forgot.

516
00:32:21,920 --> 00:32:24,912
- Um, you want to take the first shift?
- No, no, you go ahead.

517
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:26,718
Mmm.

518
00:32:47,040 --> 00:32:50,112
Tell me something,
Brackett.

519
00:32:52,320 --> 00:32:55,039
What is it about me
you don't like?

520
00:32:55,120 --> 00:32:57,156
I'm not pretty enough?

521
00:32:57,240 --> 00:33:00,118
Not tall enough?
Too tall?

522
00:33:00,200 --> 00:33:03,875
Too smart?
Not smart enough?

523
00:33:03,960 --> 00:33:06,918
Wrong colour hair?

524
00:33:07,000 --> 00:33:09,434
Talk too much?

525
00:33:09,520 --> 00:33:11,909
Really, what is it?

526
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:16,039
I've never had this effect
on a man before.

527
00:33:16,120 --> 00:33:18,236
You would be surprised,
but...

528
00:33:18,320 --> 00:33:23,474
most men are actually
somewhat attracted to me.

529
00:33:23,560 --> 00:33:27,758
I know you think I'm trouble,
and you curse the day you met me...

530
00:33:27,840 --> 00:33:31,799
but off the record, I don't feel
that way about you...

531
00:33:31,880 --> 00:33:34,030
at all.

532
00:33:40,360 --> 00:33:43,352
Off the record, Peterson...

533
00:33:43,440 --> 00:33:46,079
I don't feel that way
about you, either...

534
00:33:46,160 --> 00:33:48,230
at all.

535
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:52,116
You don't?

536
00:34:05,760 --> 00:34:08,433
First time I ever kissed
a newspaperman.

537
00:34:08,520 --> 00:34:10,875
I like it.

538
00:34:12,880 --> 00:34:18,238
This doesn't change anything.
I'm still the <i>Globe,</i> and you're still...

539
00:34:18,320 --> 00:34:21,995
The <i>Chronicle.</i>
I know, Sabrina, I know.

540
00:34:22,080 --> 00:34:25,675
- We're still...
- Competitors.

541
00:34:27,040 --> 00:34:29,873
Thank you
for calling me Sabrina.

542
00:34:41,160 --> 00:34:43,913
- Hello?
- <i>This is Mrs Hervey.</i>

543
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:47,151
<i>If you want to see my husband,</i>
<i>please come now.</i>

544
00:34:47,240 --> 00:34:51,153
This is exactly the sort of thing that
would've driven my ex-husband crazy.

545
00:34:51,240 --> 00:34:54,869
Your current husband's not
too thrilled about it, either.

546
00:34:57,440 --> 00:35:00,159
- Well...
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

547
00:35:03,680 --> 00:35:06,194
Oh, hey, don't forget
your wallet.

548
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:23,752
Shall we?

549
00:35:26,440 --> 00:35:29,113
Sure.

550
00:35:29,200 --> 00:35:34,035
My husband's home now because
there's nothing more they
can do for him at the hospital.

551
00:35:34,120 --> 00:35:37,430
But some days
he's not all that bad.

552
00:35:37,520 --> 00:35:42,389
Alex, the reporters from Chicago
are here to see you.

553
00:35:44,560 --> 00:35:46,118
Alex?

554
00:35:51,480 --> 00:35:54,119
Alex.

555
00:35:54,200 --> 00:35:58,273
Alex, they've come
such a long way to see you.

556
00:36:00,400 --> 00:36:04,473
You wanted to talk to my husband
about, um, Darryl Beekman, didn't you?

557
00:36:04,560 --> 00:36:08,314
Mm-hmm. Yes, we were wondering why,
a-after the success of LDF...

558
00:36:08,400 --> 00:36:10,994
that your husband
was given a promotion...

559
00:36:11,080 --> 00:36:13,196
but Dr Beekman chose
to leave the company?

560
00:36:13,280 --> 00:36:18,115
Were you wondering, Mr Brackett,
or do you think you know?

561
00:36:18,200 --> 00:36:20,953
We think we know. We just need
someone to tell us if we're right.

562
00:36:21,040 --> 00:36:23,952
Did your husband ever say
anything about Dr Beekman...

563
00:36:24,040 --> 00:36:25,553
about disagreements
between them?

564
00:36:25,640 --> 00:36:27,392
Never.

565
00:36:27,480 --> 00:36:31,439
I-I'm sorry. I w... I was hoping
Alex could talk to you.

566
00:36:31,520 --> 00:36:34,193
I sensed
that he wanted to.

567
00:36:36,760 --> 00:36:40,912
Uh, uh, excuse me. Can I use
your restroom for a second?

568
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:43,514
- Down the hall.
- Oh, thank you.

569
00:36:44,800 --> 00:36:47,394
I'm sorry you had to come
such a long way.

570
00:36:47,480 --> 00:36:51,598
I really appreciate you calling us,
Mrs Hervey. Thank you.

571
00:36:55,000 --> 00:36:57,639
<i>Maybe we should wait</i>
<i>until Mr Brackett gets back.</i>

572
00:36:57,720 --> 00:36:59,358
<i>No, no, that's okay.</i>

573
00:36:59,440 --> 00:37:01,590
<i>Uh, I really don't know</i>
<i>what it is, but...</i>

574
00:37:01,680 --> 00:37:05,036
I thought it was strange,
because in 30 years...

575
00:37:05,120 --> 00:37:08,908
I've never seen Alex bring
anything home from work.

576
00:37:10,920 --> 00:37:16,153
You can take it, but I'm afraid it's
not much use to anyone outside of Chess.

577
00:37:17,520 --> 00:37:19,397
Thank you.

578
00:37:45,960 --> 00:37:48,349
<i>This is Captain Riley. Just to let</i>
<i>you know that we're ahead of schedule...</i>

579
00:37:48,440 --> 00:37:51,989
<i>and we'll be arriving in Chicago</i>
<i>in just a little under an hour.</i>

580
00:37:52,080 --> 00:37:56,153
<i>The temperature is a breezy</i>
<i>34 degrees with clear skies.</i>

581
00:38:01,680 --> 00:38:04,433
- Sorry.
- No problem.

582
00:38:04,520 --> 00:38:07,512
Complimentary champagne
for the bride and groom?

583
00:38:07,600 --> 00:38:10,319
I can always spot the newlyweds
on our Vegas flights.

584
00:38:10,400 --> 00:38:12,630
Of course with you two,
who couldn't?

585
00:38:16,120 --> 00:38:18,873
- Congratulations.
- Thank you.

586
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:23,672
So, what should
we drink to?

587
00:38:26,120 --> 00:38:28,759
- Our annulment?
- Perfect!

588
00:38:28,840 --> 00:38:32,071
Because, truthfully, Brackett,
there's not a man in the world
I'd rather annul than you.

589
00:38:33,800 --> 00:38:36,678
Truthfully, Peterson, I wouldn't
believe anything you ever said...

590
00:38:36,760 --> 00:38:39,433
that started with
the word "truthfully."

591
00:38:49,200 --> 00:38:51,668
Well, I guess it's time
to put an end to the charade.

592
00:38:51,760 --> 00:38:55,799
Yeah. Gimbel's marries Macy's.
We wouldn't want that to get around.

593
00:39:07,920 --> 00:39:10,195
- May I?
- Mmm.

594
00:39:20,720 --> 00:39:24,918
Will you do something for me,
Peterson, for old times' sake?

595
00:39:27,080 --> 00:39:29,150
What?

596
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:34,275
Kiss me goodbye.

597
00:40:18,880 --> 00:40:22,634
<i>Back now, 7:30 on this, uh,</i>
<i>Monday morning, October the 14th.</i>

598
00:40:22,720 --> 00:40:25,712
<i>I'm Bryant Gumbel here in Studio 3B.</i>
<i>Katie Couric's up on Capitol...</i>

599
00:40:25,800 --> 00:40:28,234
What happened
to October 13th?

600
00:40:39,400 --> 00:40:41,277
Let's go.

601
00:40:47,720 --> 00:40:50,996
Uh, I'm here
for the 4:00 tour.

602
00:40:51,080 --> 00:40:53,548
...in beautiful
Spring Creek, Wisconsin.

603
00:40:53,640 --> 00:40:55,596
Our first stop
on today's tour...

604
00:40:55,680 --> 00:40:58,831
is going to be the Chess Family
Science Discovery Centre.

605
00:40:58,920 --> 00:41:03,357
Now, as we walk in pairs down
the Biology of Tomorrow corridor...

606
00:41:03,440 --> 00:41:06,238
Right this way, sir.
How are you folks today?

607
00:41:06,320 --> 00:41:11,519
I'd like to point out a few of the
everyday products created here at Chess.

608
00:41:11,600 --> 00:41:14,831
For example, the cold medicine
which I forgot to take this morning.

609
00:41:20,560 --> 00:41:24,109
<i>- Hi.</i>
<i>- Milk, a staple for the entire family.</i>

610
00:41:24,200 --> 00:41:27,875
<i>And just one of the products</i>
<i>Chess Chemical is working to improve...</i>

611
00:41:27,960 --> 00:41:30,713
- <i>for the 21st century.</i>
- You know, you look very familiar.
Have we met before?

612
00:41:30,800 --> 00:41:34,429
No. Actually this is my first
visit to the Twilight Zone.

613
00:41:34,520 --> 00:41:37,956
- Why'd you double-cross me, Peterson?
- Just following the Golden Rule.

614
00:41:38,040 --> 00:41:40,508
But I thought we were partners,
five-oh, five-oh.

615
00:41:40,600 --> 00:41:43,353
That must explain why you took
Kim's security pass.

616
00:41:43,440 --> 00:41:44,998
- Oh, Peterson, I was gonna...
- "I was gonna tell you."

617
00:41:45,080 --> 00:41:47,196
You can't even be honest
about being dishonest.

618
00:41:47,280 --> 00:41:50,033
I was gonna tell you, Peterson.
I took it as a backup.

619
00:41:50,120 --> 00:41:53,192
- I never thought we'd be here again.
- Yeah, mm-hmm.

620
00:41:53,280 --> 00:41:55,840
- Look, I gotta go.
- Peterson, listen.

621
00:41:55,920 --> 00:41:57,831
It's not safe for you
to be here alone.

622
00:41:57,920 --> 00:42:00,115
Now, you probably don't wanna be
reminded of this...

623
00:42:00,200 --> 00:42:03,510
but I did take an oath to protect you
till death do us part.

624
00:42:03,600 --> 00:42:05,318
Game's over, Brackett,
and you lose.

625
00:42:05,400 --> 00:42:07,356
I've got the disk.
I've got the security pass.

626
00:42:07,440 --> 00:42:09,590
Actually, I have the disk.

627
00:42:09,680 --> 00:42:11,989
Actually, that's blank.

628
00:42:12,080 --> 00:42:14,355
I've got the disk.
I've got my own security pass.

629
00:42:14,440 --> 00:42:16,715
And I've got the authority
to have you thrown out of here.

630
00:42:16,800 --> 00:42:19,758
Sabrina. Honey, come on.

631
00:42:19,840 --> 00:42:22,400
After all
we've been through!

632
00:42:22,480 --> 00:42:26,234
Just do in your heart what you know
I would do if I was in your position.

633
00:42:29,080 --> 00:42:31,036
Okay.

634
00:42:35,000 --> 00:42:36,479
Sam, stop!
I don't want to hear.

635
00:42:36,560 --> 00:42:39,233
I'm not interested in Vargas any more.
I'm off the story.

636
00:42:39,320 --> 00:42:42,756
- <i>Peterson, too?</i>
- No, no, no. She's still on it.
You know, the girl is nuts!

637
00:42:42,840 --> 00:42:46,037
- She went undercover
as a Chess tour guide.
- <i>You're kidding!</i>

638
00:42:46,120 --> 00:42:47,633
I'm serious.
She got a job there.

639
00:42:47,720 --> 00:42:49,597
<i>Pete, look, look, there's more</i>
<i>I wanna tell you, okay?</i>

640
00:42:49,680 --> 00:42:53,309
No, Sam, don't tempt me!
I'm not gonna get killed on a story
where I don't even get the girl.

641
00:42:53,400 --> 00:42:56,198
I'm goin' back on my book tour.
I'll be in Seattle by dinner.

642
00:42:56,280 --> 00:42:58,555
<i>In a few hours, this whole thing</i>
<i>will be a distant memory.</i>

643
00:42:58,640 --> 00:43:00,631
Okay, don't worry about it, buddy.
And good luck on the tour.

644
00:43:00,720 --> 00:43:03,109
<i>Thanks for everything, man.</i>

645
00:43:06,120 --> 00:43:09,271
You need to have a little chat
with your personnel director.

646
00:43:09,360 --> 00:43:12,238
Sabrina Peterson's
working at Chess.

647
00:43:12,320 --> 00:43:14,356
Oh, Jesus.

648
00:43:16,560 --> 00:43:18,710
He ain't gonna help us.

649
00:43:28,880 --> 00:43:30,871
- Here you go.
- Thank you.

650
00:43:33,520 --> 00:43:36,956
We hope you have enjoyed
your tour, and remember,
no matter where you may live...

651
00:43:37,040 --> 00:43:41,079
Chess Chemical is your neighbour,
striving for a better tomorrow today.

652
00:43:41,160 --> 00:43:43,037
Thank you very much.

653
00:43:48,040 --> 00:43:49,871
Excuse me.
Does this plane have a phone?

654
00:43:49,960 --> 00:43:52,918
Straight ahead on the
cabin wall, but you really need
to stay in your seat, sir.

655
00:43:53,000 --> 00:43:55,753
- We're about to take off.
- Okay, thanks.

656
00:44:12,080 --> 00:44:14,719
- <i>What city, please?</i>
- Uh, Madison. The number
of the capitol building.

657
00:44:14,800 --> 00:44:18,270
- <i>That's 555-4331.</i>
- Thank you.

658
00:44:19,760 --> 00:44:22,399
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,</i>
<i>we'll be taking off momentarily.</i>

659
00:44:22,480 --> 00:44:25,631
<i>Flight attendants,</i>
<i>please prepare for departure.</i>

660
00:44:25,720 --> 00:44:28,075
- <i>Good evening. State Capitol.</i>
- Yeah, Sam Smotherman.

661
00:44:28,160 --> 00:44:31,038
<i>Mr Smotherman.</i>
<i>That's extension 307.</i>

662
00:46:50,640 --> 00:46:54,235
Keep it movin'.
Keep comin'.

663
00:46:54,320 --> 00:46:57,790
Fine. Hold it right there.
Okay.

664
00:46:57,880 --> 00:47:00,474
- How you doin', Jack?
- Okay, Bob. How are you?

665
00:47:01,200 --> 00:47:03,191
Jesus! God!

666
00:47:03,280 --> 00:47:05,475
What are these...
Oh, Jesus!

667
00:47:32,400 --> 00:47:35,392
Too bad. But a definite "A"
for effort, Peterson.

668
00:47:35,480 --> 00:47:40,429
Or should I call you Brackett,
Mrs Brackett? Hmm?

669
00:47:40,520 --> 00:47:42,351
I don't really care what
you call me, Smotherman.

670
00:47:42,440 --> 00:47:46,035
Or should I call you
Ernesto, Mr Vargas?

671
00:47:46,120 --> 00:47:48,793
Oh, darn!

672
00:47:48,880 --> 00:47:51,075
I wanted to be the one
to tell you.

673
00:47:51,160 --> 00:47:53,230
You did!
A cop once told me...

674
00:47:53,320 --> 00:47:55,629
"Always look for the lie; that's when
the story begins to unravel."

675
00:47:55,720 --> 00:47:59,190
When I asked you
what year you graduated,
you gave me two different years.

676
00:47:59,280 --> 00:48:02,033
I wondered why, so I looked
you up in your yearbook.

677
00:48:02,120 --> 00:48:06,716
Funny thing was, you weren't in it,
not under the name Smotherman, anyway.

678
00:48:11,600 --> 00:48:13,875
We were hoping you had what
we were looking for, but...

679
00:48:13,960 --> 00:48:16,110
since you don't have it,
and we don't have it...

680
00:48:16,200 --> 00:48:18,668
we can assume
it didn't survive the crash.

681
00:48:18,760 --> 00:48:23,151
So now the only evidence
to destroy is you.

682
00:48:23,240 --> 00:48:26,038
Oh, and your husband,
of course.

683
00:48:26,120 --> 00:48:29,795
Fortunately,
we know exactly where he is.

684
00:48:36,080 --> 00:48:39,470
- What's going on, Ted?
- Oh, Mr Chess, I didn't know
anyone was in here.

685
00:48:39,560 --> 00:48:41,596
We've got an alert
down at the loading dock.

686
00:48:41,680 --> 00:48:45,150
- Go back to your station.
I'll deal with it.
- Yes, sir.

687
00:48:46,560 --> 00:48:49,120
Get out there.
See what's going on.

688
00:48:51,520 --> 00:48:53,715
How'd you get involved
in this, Sam?

689
00:48:53,800 --> 00:48:56,598
Willy wanted to get rid of Beekman, and
he thought you could get the job done?

690
00:48:56,680 --> 00:48:59,797
- Something like that.
- But you botched the fire in college.

691
00:48:59,880 --> 00:49:03,759
- What made him think
you'd get it right this time?
- I was the only bad guy he knew.

692
00:49:06,600 --> 00:49:08,477
Did he pay you to hook up
with Senator Robbins?

693
00:49:08,560 --> 00:49:11,120
Think I could afford
steak dinners if he didn't?

694
00:49:11,200 --> 00:49:13,111
Do me a favour, Peterson.

695
00:49:13,200 --> 00:49:15,760
Sit down.

696
00:49:35,720 --> 00:49:37,358
Stay with her,
and watch her.

697
00:50:06,400 --> 00:50:10,234
I'm sorry to keep you waiting.
It seems...

698
00:50:16,080 --> 00:50:19,311
It seems we've got a traffic jam
in the parking lot.

699
00:50:19,400 --> 00:50:22,836
I'm in no rush. As long as
we've got a couple of minutes...

700
00:50:22,920 --> 00:50:24,797
What?
You want an interview?

701
00:50:24,880 --> 00:50:28,589
Why not? Give a dying girl
her last wish.

702
00:50:28,680 --> 00:50:33,515
Why'd you do it, Willy? Why not just
admit LDF was a flop and move on?

703
00:50:33,600 --> 00:50:37,878
For ten years, Beekman and Hervey
promised me they'd iron out the kinks.

704
00:50:37,960 --> 00:50:41,873
A hundred million dollars later,
they apologized, said they were wrong.

705
00:50:41,960 --> 00:50:45,270
By then it was too late.
I mortgaged our company's future
in this thing. It had to fly!

706
00:50:45,360 --> 00:50:48,477
What were these kinks,
exactly?

707
00:50:48,560 --> 00:50:51,632
Well, let's put it this way. You can't
put a label on a carton of milk:

708
00:50:51,720 --> 00:50:55,110
"This product has been known
to cause cancer in laboratory animals."

709
00:50:55,200 --> 00:50:58,670
- And Beekman was gonna blow the whistle.
- Can you imagine?

710
00:50:58,760 --> 00:51:02,992
The guy screws up and then
he tries to bite the hand that
feeds him? Tsk, tsk, tsk, tsk.

711
00:51:16,400 --> 00:51:21,235
All right, that's it. I've had it.
Just get her out. Now!

712
00:51:21,320 --> 00:51:23,993
- Willy, let's go.
- Where's he gonna take me, Sam?

713
00:51:24,080 --> 00:51:27,436
- At least tell me how
he's gonna do it, huh?
- No comment.

714
00:51:27,520 --> 00:51:28,919
Another train crash?
Another fire?

715
00:51:29,000 --> 00:51:31,275
Hey, maybe I'll get it the
old-fashioned way like Danny Brown.

716
00:51:31,360 --> 00:51:34,591
Come on, Sam,
you're the organ grinder here!
Tell me how this ape's gonna do it.

717
00:51:36,280 --> 00:51:39,078
- Why not just show her, Mando?
- Brackett!

718
00:51:39,160 --> 00:51:40,752
Brackett.

719
00:51:42,600 --> 00:51:45,990
You got her? Just get her.
Stop shooting!

720
00:51:46,080 --> 00:51:48,913
Lock the gates.
Don't let anyone in.

721
00:52:07,200 --> 00:52:10,909
Peterson, I thought
you were one of them!

722
00:52:11,000 --> 00:52:14,754
It's okay.
I'm all right. I'm fine.

723
00:52:16,080 --> 00:52:19,038
What'd you come back for,
Brackett, me or the story?

724
00:52:20,360 --> 00:52:23,557
- Mostly you, Peterson.
- Mostly me?

725
00:52:24,320 --> 00:52:26,515
He's on the third tier!

726
00:53:27,240 --> 00:53:29,674
Nice try, Mando.
Drop the gun.

727
00:53:29,760 --> 00:53:33,036
Why? Are you going to shoot me
with your finger, Brackett?

728
00:53:33,120 --> 00:53:35,190
There's only one way
to find out.

729
00:54:15,520 --> 00:54:17,909
Any time you want to jump in,
Peterson.

730
00:54:37,320 --> 00:54:39,231
- Thank you!
- You're welcome.

731
00:54:52,840 --> 00:54:55,513
Oh, Jesus.

732
00:55:05,480 --> 00:55:07,914
Oh, Jesus!

733
00:55:25,960 --> 00:55:29,873
My mother always said, you want
the job done right, do it yourself.

734
00:55:32,440 --> 00:55:34,510
Whoa. Whoa.

735
00:55:38,440 --> 00:55:41,989
- Peterson!
- Self-defense classes.
A must for a woman in the '90s.

736
00:55:42,080 --> 00:55:43,832
Uh-huh.

737
00:55:45,160 --> 00:55:48,436
- Stay there or I'll shoot.
- I don't think so.

738
00:55:54,360 --> 00:55:56,555
Think again.

739
00:56:33,800 --> 00:56:36,917
Mrs Brackett,
you had it all the time.

740
00:56:43,320 --> 00:56:45,470
Uh-uh-uh.
Don't touch.

741
00:56:49,440 --> 00:56:52,352
Hey, Pete, do you mind
if I kill your wife?

742
00:56:52,440 --> 00:56:55,477
As a matter of fact, I do.
Hang on, Peterson!

743
00:57:01,800 --> 00:57:03,631
Grab on!

744
00:57:19,400 --> 00:57:21,914
I got it! I got it.

745
00:57:23,240 --> 00:57:24,912
Atta girl.

746
00:57:38,480 --> 00:57:40,436
"As Vargas shouted
his final command...

747
00:57:40,520 --> 00:57:43,637
the Thin Man's eyes
measured Peterson for a coffin.

748
00:57:43,720 --> 00:57:47,235
She turned, a breath away from
the barrel of his.22 automatic."

749
00:57:47,320 --> 00:57:50,630
Poetry, sweetheart.
Absolute poetry!

750
00:57:50,720 --> 00:57:55,111
Look who's talking. "The cold metal tip
of the pistol brushed against my hair.

751
00:57:55,200 --> 00:57:58,954
I looked up at the assassin. His eyes
were empty as two holes in a mask."

752
00:58:00,560 --> 00:58:03,279
Honey, I got goose bumps!

753
00:58:03,360 --> 00:58:06,079
You ever think
of writing a novel?

754
00:58:06,160 --> 00:58:08,151
And give up the newspaper game?
Never.

755
00:58:11,200 --> 00:58:12,952
Okay!

756
00:58:15,760 --> 00:58:19,389
Well, I might give it a try again.
Here's my idea.

757
00:58:19,480 --> 00:58:23,393
- Mmm.
- Male, female reporters
solve mystery...

758
00:58:23,480 --> 00:58:26,916
- fight,
- Mm-hmm.
- make up, fall in love...

759
00:58:27,000 --> 00:58:29,275
save the day,
go on a honeymoon.

760
00:58:29,360 --> 00:58:31,999
Sounds like a best-seller
to me.

761
00:58:33,480 --> 00:58:35,869
- Darling.
- Yes, my love?

762
00:58:35,960 --> 00:58:40,511
You didn't really mean it when
you said our scoundrel days
were behind us, did you?

763
00:58:45,400 --> 00:58:48,756
They are for me
if they are for you.

764
00:58:48,840 --> 00:58:51,912
All right. I promise
to go straight if you do.

765
00:58:53,720 --> 00:58:56,280
I do.

766
00:58:57,960 --> 00:59:00,269
Then I do too.

767
00:59:09,240 --> 00:59:11,151
Brackett, get this!

768
00:59:11,240 --> 00:59:13,913
- Two guys with.38s coming right
out of that, uh, that bank.
- Peterson.

769
00:59:14,000 --> 00:59:17,709
Peterson, sweetheart.
We're on our honeymoon.

770
00:59:17,800 --> 00:59:20,234
Sorry, baby.
It slipped my mind.

771
00:59:20,320 --> 00:59:22,959
Let me refresh
your memory.

772
00:59:28,040 --> 00:59:29,792
Uh-uh.

